  "Idea": "We propose 'Dynamic Meta-Calibration for Few-Shot Learning in Massively Multilingual Language Models'—a novel framework that integrates meta-learning with adaptive calibration to address miscalibration in low-resource languages during few-shot inference. Current calibration techniques (e.g., temperature scaling) are typically applied uniformly or tuned on held-out validation sets, which are often unavailable for under-resourced languages. Moreover, few-shot learning introduces new uncertainty dynamics: while adding examples may improve accuracy, it can also distort confidence distributions due to domain mismatch or syntactic divergence. Our framework addresses this by training a meta-calibrator—a lightweight neural module that observes the model’s behavior across multiple few-shot episodes and language contexts during meta-training, and learns to predict optimal calibration transformations at inference time.\n\nThe meta-calibrator takes as input language-specific features (e.g., script family, typological distance from English, token frequency), few-shot sample characteristics (e.g., lexical overlap, syntactic complexity), and intermediate model outputs (e.g., entropy trajectories, confidence variance across shots). Based on these inputs, it dynamically selects or generates calibration parameters (e.g., temperature, Dirichlet priors, or affine transformations on logits) tailored to each language-task pair. Crucially, the meta-calibrator is trained using a meta-objective that jointly optimizes both accuracy and calibration metrics (e.g., Expected Calibration Error, Brier Score) across a curated distribution of languages spanning varying resource levels and linguistic families.\n\nThis approach enables the system to generalize calibration strategies to unseen languages by leveraging analogical reasoning from similar typological or resource profiles. For instance, if the model encounters a new low-resource Dravidian language, the meta-calibrator might apply 