  "Experiment": "Our experimental design unfolds in three stages: (1) Architecture Integration and Pre-training, (2) Meta-Calibration Training, and (3) Few-Shot Evaluation & Generalization Testing.\n\nIn Stage 1, we integrate the Calibration Controller Module (CCM) into a base MMLM (e.g., mT5 or XLM-R). The CCM consists of a small MLP that takes as input language-level features (script family, WordSim distance from English, average token frequency) and instance-level signals (few-shot lexical overlap, input entropy). It outputs modulation vectors applied multiplicatively to attention softmax temperatures and feed-forward network gates at each layer. These operations are fully differentiable and initialized to identity (no change) before training.\n\nIn Stage 2, we train the augmented model using a meta-learning regime across 45 languages spanning six families and three resource tiers. Each training episode simulates few-shot scenarios (1–8 shots) on tasks like NLI (XNLI), QA (MLQA), and classification (BUCC). The loss function combines cross-entropy with a dynamic calibration penalty weighted by estimated uncertainty. We use curriculum learning to gradually increase typological difficulty. The CCM is updated end-to-end alongside the main model.\n\nIn Stage 3, we evaluate on 15 held-out languages, including zero-shot transfers and few-shot adaptation. Baselines include standard fine-tuning, post-hoc temperature scaling, and the original Dynamic Meta-Calibration. Metrics include accuracy, F1, ECE, MCE, and calibration stability across shot variations. We conduct ablation studies removing typological inputs or disabling feedback loops. Ideal outcomes: (a) ≥40% reduction in ECE for low-resource languages vs. strongest baseline, (b) <2% drop in accuracy (ideally improvement), (c) faster inference than two-stage calibration methods, (d) strong generalization to unseen languages with similar typology, and (e) interpretable attention patterns showing reduced overconfidence 